<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">FBA0017/13-14</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 45.35pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-45.35pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The Law Society of England and Wales—Written evidence</span></h2><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Law Society of England and Wales (the ‘Society') is the professional body representing more than 166,000 solicitors in England and Wales. It works globally to support and represent its members, promoting the highest professional standards and the rule </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of law.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The submission has been prepared in consultation with the Tax Law Committee of the Law Society of England and Wales. The Committee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is a specialist body of the Society comprised of practitioners and experts in domestic and international tax issue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> whose purpose is to review, and promote improvements in, tax law and procedure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Overview</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC's consultation on Partnerships</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, launched in May 2013, and the subsequent Technical Note and Guidance</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> illustrate where the new approach to tax policy making could be said to be failing. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC has presented an unfortunate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">consequence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of existing legislation, which has the effect of reducing tax receipts below the level that they might have been, as “tax a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">voidance”.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The Law Society understands and supports the Government’s desire to tackle tax avoidance. The Society accepts that some of the behaviours which the proposals in the May 2013 consultation are designed to address would fall into that category. Ho</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wever, the Society is concerned that presenting the consequences of differing tax rates applying to different types of partner (individual or corporate) and the flexibility in profit sharing arrangements inherent in UK partnership law, as “avoidance” is mi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sleading.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Society is also concerned that significant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">piecemeal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">changes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to be made to the tax treatment of partnerships in Finance Bill 2014, both under this consultation and the consultation on loan relationships</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, when the Office of Tax Simplif</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ication Report on partnerships is about to emerge.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Law Society believes that HMRC's consultation process was flawed.  HMRC has acknowledged that many respondents were concerned that the proposal from May 2013 would create legal uncertainty. HMRC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also acknowledged</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that respondents had </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recommended a minor legislative amendment which would have satisfied the stated policy objective without causing any undesirable consequences. Instead of pursuing such an amendment, HMRC has adopted a radically diffe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rent approach in the December 2013 Technical Note and Guidance from that which it sought comments on in the May 2013 consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> As far as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Society </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aware, the new approach is not reflected in the responses to the original May 2013 consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, HMRC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> adhere to the original implementation timetable giving the excuse that “there has been a long lead time for customers to prepare for these changes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the commentary in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Summary of Reponses </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Government also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">seeks to relate back </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its new</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">propos</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">als</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to the May consultation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> despite the approach in the December document being </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">significantly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">differe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nt from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the proposals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">canvassed in May.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Law Society raises serious concerns that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ffect is that there was no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">real</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> consultation on t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he proposals currently in the draft Finance Bill </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">prior to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">December 2013. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h5 style="font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 119.05pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Taxation of Partnerships</span></h5><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-45.35pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#ff0000; display:none; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In our view, the development of the proposals for the taxation of Salaried Members of UK LLPs has been most unsatisfactory and represents a significant </span><span style="color:#ff0000; display:none; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">departure from HM Treasury’s approach to the making of tax policy as set out in “Tax Policy making: a new approach” (June 2010).</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The background to the proposed changes to the taxation of members of LLPs regarded as salaried members starts with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the introduction of LLPs by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Limited Liability Partnerships Act 2000 (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">LLPA 2000</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Act </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">intended </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that the status of a person who is a partner in a general partnership and a person who (although he may purport to be a partner in a general partnership)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is in law an employee of the partnership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> should not change </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">if</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the general partnership convert</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to an LLP (Tiffin v Lester Aldridge LLP [2012] IRLR 391; Clyde &amp; Co LLP v Bates Van </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Winkelhof</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> [2012] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 1207). The former would be a member of the newly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">formed LLP and the latter would be an employee of it (but would, in addition, be a member of it if registered as such). This parity of treatment was secured by LLPA 2000 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s.4(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The original tax policy was to provide the same equivalence of treatment (HMR</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">C: “Partnerships: A review of two aspects of the tax rules” (May 2013), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 2.8). However, this policy misfired, because </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Income Tax (Trading and Other Income) Act 2005 (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ITTOIA 2005</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> s.863 provides that, where an LLP carries on a trade, its trading activit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ies are treated as carried on in partnership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">by its members</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. To achieve equivalence of tax treatment, ITTOIA 2005 s.863 should have provided for the LLP’s trading activities to be treated as carried on in partnership </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">by those of its members who, if it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">were a general partnership, would be partners in the partnership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. By failing to make such provision, ITTOIA 2005 s.863 had (and continues to have) the effect </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> treating as self-employed for tax purposes members of the LLP (“LLP employee members”) who, if</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it were a general partnership, would be employees of the partnership (e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> those</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> salaried “partners” who are not in law partners at all).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In “Partnerships: A review of two aspects of the tax rules” (May 2013), HMRC proposed to put a stop to the inadvert</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ent taxation of LLP employee members as self-employed by providing that such members would be treated as employees (“salaried members”) for tax purposes if:</span></li></ol><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">they would be regarded as employees of the partnership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> if the partnership were a general partnershi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">p </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(which, at first glance, is effectively an alignment of ITTOIA 2005 s.863 with LLPA 2000 s.4(4)) (“the first condition”); or</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">their membership of the LLP does not bear any economic risk, they are not entitled to share of the profits and they are not ent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">led to a share of any surplus assets on a winding-up (“the second condition”).</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">regards </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the first condition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC proposed that its application should be determined by reference to the general tests for determining whether a person is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">employed or self-employed (as set out in the Employment Status Manual</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">), rather than by simply amending ITTOIA 2005 s.863 so that it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">conformed with LLPA 2000 s.4(4).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The consultation closed on 9 August 2013 and HMRC received about 110 written responses, p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rincipally from business, the professions and their representative bodies. Consultation meetings were also held with some of these respondents and other interested parties.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Like others, the Society</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recommended </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that there should be absolute consistency bet</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ween general employment law and tax law. Accordingly, if an individual is a self-employed partner in a general partnership or a self-employed member of an LLP for general employment law purposes, he or she should also be self-employed for tax purposes. Con</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">versely, if an individual is an employee of a general partnership or an LLP for general employment law purposes, he or she should also be an employee for tax purposes. We therefore recommended that there should be a simple amendment of ITTOIA 2005 s.863 so</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that it conforms with LLPA 2000 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s.4(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4)). </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Additionally, like others</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Society </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">objected to the use of the inappropriate tests in the Employment Status Manual in applying the first condition. Whether an individual is a self-employed member, or an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">employee, of an LLP should be decided by reference to the case law tests in Tiffin and Clyde &amp; Co LLP. The Employment Status Manual is not aimed at partnerships but at the wider question</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> whether, in relation to any kind of employer (e.g.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a company), an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> individual is an employee of the employer or a self-employed independent contractor in relation to the employer.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The new policy announced on 10 December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC’s response to the May 2013 consultation was published </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">10 December 2013 (HMRC: “Partners</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hips: A review of two aspects of the tax rules: Technical Note and Guidance” (10 December 2013)). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Law Society understands that the Government's </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">response </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> met with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">widespread concern </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by business and the professions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The response </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">abandoned the first </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and second conditions from the May 2013 consultation and rejected the simple approach of amending ITTOIA 2005 s.863 so that it conforms with LLPA 2000 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s.4(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4)).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Instead, HMRC proposed that a member of an LLP would be treated as an employee (“a salaried </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">member”) for tax purposes if:</span></li></ol><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">his or her remuneration (“disguised salary”) is wholly, or substantially wholly, fixed or, if it is variable, it varies otherwise than by reference to the LLP’s overall profits or losses (“Condition A”);</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he or she does not hav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e significant influence over the LLP’s affairs (“Condition B”); and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">his</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> or her contribution to the LLP is less than 25% of the disguised salary (“Condition C”).</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is a fundamentally different approach from that set out in the May 2013 consultation. HMRC justified the abandonment of the first condition on the grounds of the objections to the use of the tests in the Employment Status Manual. It justified the reje</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ction of the proposal to follow the test in LLPA 2000 s.4(4) on the grounds of a general lack of agreement over the interpretation of the case law in this area (such as Tiffin and Clyde &amp; Co LLP) (December 2013 Summary of Responses, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">paras</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 3.10 to 3.14). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e Law Society does not agree with this statement, which we do not believe is supported by any analysis in the Summary of Responses. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Finally, HMRC said that Conditions A to C were a strengthening of the second condition. We do not agree</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as we believe that t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hey</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are a fundamentally different </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">proposal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We do not object in principle to a case law test being replaced by a series of objective tests, provided that in essence they replicate the case law test and respect the tax principle </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">underlying</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the case law tes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t. An example of this is the new</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> statutory</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> residence test which has been generally welcomed as a simpler and more objective approach than the case law test but which also respects the relevant tax principle (in that case, the aspect of the territoriality o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f UK tax that is based on residence). Unfortunately, the objective tests set out in Conditions A to C completely fail both to replicate the case law tests and to respect the tax principle that they embody.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We will be making detailed representations to HMR</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">C on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">our concerns about</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Conditions A to C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, we object to the new approach set out in the December 2013 Technical Note on the following grounds:</span></li></ol><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Condition A does not address the correct question, namely</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> whether the individual’s remuneration results</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from a division of the LLP’s profits or represents an expense in arriving at those profits. It merely addresses the computatio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nal aspects of the payment.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Condition B assumes that all individuals carrying on business in common have significant influence ov</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">er the affairs of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> whole</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> business. In large modern partnerships, the contribution of some partners is predominantly managerial and that of others predominantly client-orientated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> technical. Influence is, therefore, a common indicator of partner status but it is n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ot a defining or conclusive one.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Condition C must be welcomed in that it will rescue many individuals who on any view would be partners if the LLP were a general partnersh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ip but who fail Conditions A and B. However, there are two objections to Condition C. First, a substantial capital contribution may be a common indicator of partner status but it is not a defining or conclusive one. Second, some highly profitable professio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nal LLPs require relatively little capital. Condition C may cause such LLPs to raise more capital than is commercially necessary. If so, this would be an example of tax law distorting commercial decisions.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The commercial consequences of the proposed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">approach</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If the new approach set out in the December 2013 Technical Note becomes law, it will, in our view, have the following harmful consequences:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will create an inconsistency between the taxation of general partnerships and foreign LLPs operating i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n the UK on the one hand and that of UK LLPs on the other. This inconsistency will put UK LLPs at a competitive disadvantage;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> competitive disadvantage will not be confined to the taxation of Salaried Members but will extend to the administration of ta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">x. In most professional partnerships, partners leave the tax element of their profits in the partnerships as working capital until it is needed to pay the tax. This applies even if, under the new proposals, the partner would be a Salaried Member if the gen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eral partnership were an LLP. By contrast, if the present proposals become law, Salaried Members of LLPs will not be able to leave the tax element of their so-called disguised salary in the LLPs as working capital until it is needed to pay the tax. It will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be deducted at source and paid to HMRC on a monthly basis.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This will decimate the working capital reserves of many firms at a time when there are precious few other sources of finance.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The consultation process</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Law Society is concerned that t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he consu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ltation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">process surrounding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">partnerships </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has been a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">optimal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">example of how tax policy should be developed and new law made.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HM Treasury’s “Tax policy making: a new approach” (June 2010) sets out three stages to the development of tax policy and says </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that, generally, there should be consultation at each of those stages. In this case, neither the proposals in the May 2013 consultation nor those in the December 2013 technical note were preceded by any consultation. Both came to inter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ested parties “out of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the blue”. Further shortcomings include the following:</span></li></ol><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">although</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the December 2013 technical note is a very different proposition from the May 2013 consultation, the time scale for introducing the new law is the same</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 6 April 2014. The time taken to bring </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">out the December 2013 technical note (4 months from the closing of the May 2013 consultation) means that business and the professions have been left with only 4 months to prepare for a fundamentally different set of tax rules affecting a core aspect of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ir operations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with the support of ambiguous guidance.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">what started as a moderate and sensible proposal to counteract obvious tax avoidance (e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> potato pickers being corralled into LLPs) has become, a widespread attack on a business model which is of cent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ral importance to the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> legal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> profession and an increasing number of other businesses;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the December 2013 technical note brushes aside the suggestion made by many respondents to the May 2013 consultation that the test in LLPA 2000 s.4(4) should be followed for tax purposes and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">instead </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">proposes three new conditions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The Law Society is concerne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d by this lack of transparency and questions whether the integrity of a consolation process has been undermined.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> consultation considers just two aspects of the tax rules relating to partnerships. Such a piecemeal approach is not conducive to making bet</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ter tax law. In our view, it would be better to delay the introduction of the present proposals until the Office of Tax Simplification has completed its review of all aspects of the taxation of partnerships.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h5 style="font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 119.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">New Approach </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Tax Policy Making</span></h5><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As indicated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> above, </span><span style="