quoted Eurobond exemption</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">might be restricted where bonds were held by group companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and the proposal to introduce clauses limiting the application of the UK’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">double tax treaties where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">avoidance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">”</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> was identified</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in the consultation response</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, represent two cases in which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">proposals were not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ultimately</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> followed through.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">While i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t could</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be said that the consultation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">process </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">revealed that a change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in policy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> was inappropriate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">because the scope of the consultation was too limited</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in the first place</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the important point was the inappropriate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or damaging </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">legislation was avoided.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Less </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">effective consultations</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In contrast, an e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">xample of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a consultation which resulted in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> UK tax legislation being lengthened</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">without</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">being</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> obvious that the tax relief</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which it introduced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> provide an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> appropriate or useful</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> incentive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is that relating to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Employee shareholder shares</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> In that case, only</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a very small number of respondents had supported the idea that additional reliefs were required</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">While the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Law Society Tax Law </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Committee recogni</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">there may be cases in which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the usual 12 week period </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for consultation has to be curtailed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">this should be reserved for the most egregious cases where there is a real risk to the exchequer.  One </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">important document</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> was released with a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> very</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> limited period for consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> was that which de</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">procurem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Law Society does not believe that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> there was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">need </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">restrict </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">period for consultation in this case.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> particular concern was that it was not clear the extent to which the joint bidders </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for contracts might be affected or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the extent to which transactions to obtain a tax advantage would be regarded as disqualifying bidders </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on the basis that they</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> constitut</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> unacceptable avoidance.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Law Society also has concerns about the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">consultation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">regarding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the legislation dealing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">loans to participators</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  This legislation has recently been amended without consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It was also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the subject of a further consultation where, in response to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">consultees</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the Government has announced that no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">further action is to be taken. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> legi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">slation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">represented as being to curb avoidance relating to employment income</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and the Society is concerned that t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">his behaviour </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">en</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mislabelled</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as avoidance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Additionally, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">need </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">legislation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">could have been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">superseded</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> once the advance corporation tax regime (requiring ACT to be accounted for when dividends were paid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> was repealed in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">199</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A further example of behavio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r being </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mislabelled</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as avoidance is the claiming of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">corresponding adjustments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> under the transfer prici</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng legislation. Transfer pricing used to apply only to cross-border transactions. In response to developments in EU law, the government chose to exten</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the legislation to UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK transactions, despite being advised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> this was not necessary. Having provided that a tax advantage accruing to a UK enterprise on a transaction with a connected UK party should be denied by the transfer pricing legislation, the government then decided to give a “corresponding adjustment” to t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he connected UK party</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This took the form of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a favourable tax adjustment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which corresponded to the tax advantage which had been denied.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> It was obvious that, if the connected UK party paid tax at a higher rate, the corresponding adjustment would be more va</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">luable than the tax advantage which had been denied.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Indeed this is what happens in a cross-border context where the tax rates in different jurisdictions themselves differ.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">An example would be where the first party is a company and the second party is an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">individual who is a higher rate taxpayer. Nevertheless, the clear objective of the corresponding adjustment provisions was that UK taxpayers should claim </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">such adjustments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> where the transfer pricing legislation had the effect of denying a tax advantage on a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK transaction. Claiming corresponding adjustments is not avoidance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">because it accords with the statutory intention. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nnual </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ax on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nveloped </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">wellings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> was originally announced as part of a package of measures intended to defer perceived </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Stamp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Duty Land Tax (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">SDLT</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> avoidance.  The package taken together was intended to encourage non-individual holders of property (e.g. companies and partnerships), to “de-envelope” the property</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> i.e.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> return it to individual ownership.  One consequence of that wo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uld be that if an individual was domiciled outside the UK, but owned a UK property at the time of his death</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> inheritance tax might be paid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> although were there to be a debt secured on the property, this would reduce the amount that was chargeable.  Subseq</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uently, inheritance tax legislation was changed to reduce the scope for reducing the liability in respect of UK property </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">debts.  This may have had the perverse effect that individuals are now resigned to paying</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Annual Tax on Enveloped Dwellings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ATED</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">but not de-enveloping properties.  It is not clear if this is the intended aim of the two policies taken together.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This having been said, once the policy for the introduction of ATED was properly articulated, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Society believes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that the process to pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">duce legislation and guidance was exemplary.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">              </span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-22.7pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">A review of two aspects of the Tax Rules on </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">Partnerships,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt"> published on 20 May 2013 and ran until 9 August 2013. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-22.7pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">Issued on 10 December 2013.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">https://www.gov.uk/government/cons